      "lessonCode": "201-3A",
      "title": "201-3A - Safe Isolation Procedures",
      "unit": "Unit 201",
      "topic": "Procedures for establishing a safe working environment",
      "objectiveSummary": "Identify and explain the procedures for ensuring electrical systems are safe to work on using JIB safe isolation methods.",
      "focusText": "This lesson covers the specific steps required to isolate an electrical system safely, the implications of not following these procedures, and the selection of correct tools for verification.",
      "sourceRefs": [
        "Unit 201 Learning Outcome 3"
      ],
      "teachChecks": [
        {
          "title": "The Purpose and Implications of Safe Isolation",
          "objective": "Explain why safe isolation is mandatory and the risks to self and building systems if it is omitted."
        },
        {
          "title": "JIB Safe Isolation Steps",
          "objective": "Identify the sequence of the JIB safe isolation procedure, including the use of locking devices and warning signs."
        }
      ],
      "workedExampleObjective": "Walk through the process of isolating a single-phase circuit, from identifying the point of isolation to verifying the test lamp on a known source.",
      "guidedPracticeObjective": "Given a scenario of a domestic consumer unit, the learner must select the correct sequence of steps to isolate a lighting circuit and verify the tester.",
      "practiceObjective": "List the necessary equipment and the 10-step sequence required to safely isolate a three-phase distribution board.",
      "integrativeObjective": "Explain in detail why verifying the voltage indicator against a known source both before and after testing the circuit is the most critical part of the procedure."
    },
    {
      "lessonCode": "203-4A",
      "title": "203-4A - Earthing System Arrangements",
      "unit": "Unit 203",
      "topic": "Earthing systems and ADS components",
      "objectiveSummary": "Distinguish between the three main types of earthing systems: TT, TN-S, and TN-C-S.",
      "focusText": "This lesson focuses on identifying the characteristics of different earthing arrangements and the component parts of the earth loop impedance path.",
      "sourceRefs": [
        "Unit 203 Learning Outcome 4"
      ],
      "teachChecks": [
        {
          "title": "Types of Earthing Systems",
          "objective": "Define and identify the configurations for TT, TN-S, and TN-C-S systems."
        },
        {
          "title": "Components of the Earth Loop Path",
          "objective": "Identify the roles of the MET, CPC, and the supplier's earth return path in the ADS process."
        }
      ],
      "workedExampleObjective": "Identify a TN-C-S system by observing the combined neutral and earth conductor at the service head and tracing the path to the MET.",
      "guidedPracticeObjective": "Analyze a diagram of a TN-S system to identify the separate protective conductor provided by the supplier's cable sheath.",
      "practiceObjective": "Compare a TT system to a TN-C-S system, specifically identifying the requirement for an earth electrode in the TT arrangement.",
      "integrativeObjective": "Explain how the earth loop impedance path (Zs) is formed by combining the external loop (Ze) and the circuit conductors (R1+R2)."
